From 9e4a1fec589bb88f0bfd5d40bc4527622a6d5d26 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Wendy Labs <engineering@wendy.dev>
Date: Wed, 15 Jul 2026 16:26:06 +1000
Subject: [PATCH] flash-init: accept host medium-eject as a LUN release signal

A macOS host cannot issue the SCSI power-off Linux's udisksctl uses to
release a flashpkg/rootfs LUN; diskutil eject only ejects the medium and
never drops the UDC, so wait_for_disconnect (which polls only the UDC
state) hangs forever and the device never advances to the next LUN.

The mass_storage LUN is removable, so the gadget clears its backing file
when the host ejects the medium. Treat an emptied backing file as the
host having finished with this LUN, alongside the existing UDC-disconnect
check. Lets the macOS recovery installer advance with a plain eject.

Upstream-Status: Inappropriate [wendy-specific]
---
 init-flash.sh | 8 ++++++++
 1 file changed, 8 insertions(+)

diff --git a/init-flash.sh b/init-flash.sh
index 42b75ed..c374c1b 100755
--- a/init-flash.sh
+++ b/init-flash.sh
@@ -112,6 +112,14 @@ wait_for_disconnect() {
 	    echo "[disconnected]"
 	    break
 	fi
+	# A macOS host cannot send the SCSI power-off Linux uses to release a
+	# LUN; diskutil eject only ejects the medium. The LUN is removable, so
+	# the gadget clears its backing file on eject — an emptied file means
+	# the host has finished with this LUN.
+	if [ -z "$(cat /sys/kernel/config/usb_gadget/l4t/functions/mass_storage.l4t_storage/lun.0/file 2>/dev/null)" ]; then
+	    echo "[medium ejected]"
+	    break
+	fi
 	sleep 1
 	count=$(expr $count \+ 1)
 	if [ $count -ge 5 ]; then
-- 
